## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Timeout Enforcement Pattern

### Why it breaks on .NET 8

`Thread.Abort()` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` — the runtime no longer supports forcible thread termination. `Thread.ResetAbort()` and catching `ThreadAbortException` are also dead code.

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        return ExecuteWithTimeout(
            token => work(), timeout, CancellationToken.None);
    }

    // Preferred overload — pass the token into your work
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work,
        TimeSpan timeout,
        CancellationToken externalToken = default)
    {
        using var cts = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(externalToken);
        cts.CancelAfter(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (!externalToken.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### What changed and why

| Before (.NET Framework) | After (.NET 8) | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `new Thread(...)` + `thread.Start()` | `Task.Run(...)` | Thread pool is more efficient; `Task` integrates with cancellation |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | Token-based cancellation via `CancelAfter` | Cooperative model — no forcible abort |
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (triggered automatically by `CancelAfter`) | `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` + `ResetAbort()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` | New exception type for cooperative cancellation |
| No cancellation token plumbing | `Func<CancellationToken, T>` overload | Work **must** check the token for cancellation to actually stop |

### Critical pitfall: the token-unaware overload

The first overload (`Func<T> work`) preserves your old API signature but has **the same fundamental flaw as the original** — if `work` ignores the token, it keeps running on a thread-pool thread after timeout. The task becomes "fire and forget." Unlike `Thread.Abort`, there is **no way to forcibly stop it**.

**Always prefer the second overload** and make your work cooperate:

```csharp
// ✅ Good — work checks the token
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in largeCollection)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return ComputeResult();
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ⚠️  Bad — work ignores the token, runs to completion even after timeout
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    _ => VerySlowUnmodifiableCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### If you truly can't modify the work

Move it to a **child process** and call `Process.Kill()` on timeout — that's the only reliable replacement for the old `Thread.Abort` behavior against uncooperative code.

### Checklist

- ✅ No `Thread.Abort`, `ThreadAbortException`, or `ResetAbort`
- ✅ `CancellationTokenSource` disposed via `using`
- ✅ Timeout mapped to `CancelAfter`
- ✅ `OperationCanceledException` converted to `TimeoutException`
- ✅ External cancellation distinguished from timeout via `when` filter
- ✅ Token forwarded through the call chain
